{% block pageTitle %}
{{ pageTitle }}
{% endblock %}

{% block header %}
{% include "common/templates/partials/header.njk" %}
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
{# include errorSummary partial #}
{{ super() }}

<div class="govuk-grid-row">
    <div class="govuk-grid-column-two-thirds">
        <h1 class="govuk-heading-l">
            {{ pageTitle }}
        </h1>

        <p>
            This accessibility statement applies to the website located at <br>
            <a href="https://hmpps-assessments.service.justice.gov.uk">https://hmpps-assessments.service.justice.gov.uk</a>
        </p>
        <p>
            This website is run by the HMPPS Digital team. We want as many people as possible to be able to use this website. For example, that means you should be able to:
            <ul class="govuk-body"> 
                <li> 
                    change colours, contrast levels and fonts
                </li>
                <li> 
                    navigate most of the website using just a keyboard
                </li>
                <li> 
                    navigate most of the website using speech recognition software
                </li>
                <li> 
                    listen to most of the website using a screen reader (including the most recent versions of JAWS, NVDA and VoiceOver)
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
             We’ve also made the website text as simple as possible to understand.
        </p>
         <p>
             <a href="https://mcmw.abilitynet.org.uk/">AbilityNet</a> has advice on making your device easier to use if you have a disability.
        </p>
        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            How accessible this website is
        </h2>
        <p>
           We know some parts of this website are not fully accessible:
            <ul class="govuk-body"> 
                <li> 
                    Screen reader users may find issues with heading structures and descriptions of headings throughout the service. 
                </li>
                <li> 
                    If accessed on a mobile device or smaller screens, users may experience overlapping of check boxes with other content.
                </li>
                <li> 
                    The help PDF is currently not fully accessible for screen readers.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Feedback and contact information
        </h2>
        <p>
            If you need information on this website in a different format like accessible PDF, large print, easy read: <br>
            <br>We’ll consider your request and get back to you within 5 working days.
        </p>
        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Reporting accessibility problems with this website
        </h2>
        <p>
            We’re always looking to improve the accessibility of this website. If you find any problems not listed on this page or think we’re not meeting accessibility requirements, contact us via email: assessments-help@digital.justice.gov.uk
        </p>
         <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Enforcement procedure
        </h2>
        <p>
            The Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) is responsible for enforcing the Public Sector Bodies (Websites and Mobile Applications) (No. 2) Accessibility Regulations 2018 (the ‘accessibility regulations’). If you’re not happy with how we respond to your complaint, 
            <a href="https://www.equalityadvisoryservice.com/">contact the Equality Advisory and Support Service (EASS)</a>
        </p>
        <br>
        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Technical information about this website’s accessibility
        </h2>
        <p>
            HMPPS is committed to making its website accessible, in accordance with the Public Sector Bodies (Websites and Mobile Applications) (No. 2) Accessibility Regulations 2018.
        </p>
        <br>
        <h3 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Compliance status
        </h3>
        <p>
           This website is partially compliant with the <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines version 2.1</a>
            AA standard, due to the non-compliances and exemptions listed below. 
        </p>
         <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Non-accessible content
        </h2>
         <h2 class="govuk-heading-s">
            Non-compliance with the accessibility regulations
        </h2>
           <ul class="govuk-body"> 
                <li> 
                    Some headings may not be best placed within page structures, or unclear without context. This could be confusing for users using screen readers. These fail WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships).
                </li>
                <br>
                <li> 
                    The back button on the service has been assigned an unhelpful role that is deemed to add clutter for screen readers. This fails WCAG 2.1 success criterion 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value).
                </li>
                <br>
                <li> 
                    Some buttons or headings are non-descriptive for screen readers use, which without context can be unclear. These fail WCAG 2.1 success criterion 2.4.6 (Headings and Labels). 
                </li>
                <br>
                <li>
                    If accessed on a mobile device or smaller screens, users could experience overlapping of tables with interactive checkboxes.This fail WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.4.10 (Reflow). 
                </li>
                <br>
                <li>
                    We provide a help PDF to users of this service, however PDF’s are not very accessible and this one failed WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.1.1; 1.3.1; 2.4.2; 3.3.2; 4.1.2. We plan to convert this PDF document into HTML which will clear up all of these issues, this change is planned in our roadmap. 
                </li>
            </ul>
         <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            What we’re doing to improve accessibility
        </h2>
        <p>
            We are working through our list of changes based on feedback from an accessibility audit and users, to make sure that the service is accessible, we plan to have fixed these issues by October 2022.
        </p>
        <br>
        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Preparation of this accessibility statement
        </h2>
        <p>
            This statement was prepared on 14/07/2022. It was last reviewed on 13/07/2022.<br>
            <br>This website was last tested on 16th February 2022. The test was carried out by the Digital Accessibility Centre.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>
{% endblock %}